# Python Code Style

## Type Hints
- Add type hints to all function signatures (parameters and return types)
- Use `X | None` over `Optional[X]` (Python 3.10+)
- Use `list[str]` over `List[str]` (Python 3.9+ lowercase generics)
- For complex types, define `TypeAlias` or use `TypeVar` for generics

## Naming
- `snake_case` for functions, variables, modules
- `PascalCase` for classes
- `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` for module-level constants
- Prefix private attributes with `_`, name-mangled with `__`

## Structure
- Keep functions under 30 lines; extract helpers when longer
- One class per file for large classes; related small classes can share
- Imports: stdlib first, blank line, third-party, blank line, local
- Use `if __name__ == "__main__":` guard in scripts

## Style
- Use f-strings over `.format()` or `%`
- Prefer `pathlib.Path` over `os.path`
- Use context managers (`with`) for file and resource handling
- Use list/dict/set comprehensions when they improve readability
- Avoid bare `except:`; catch specific exceptions

## Docstrings
- Use Google-style or NumPy-style docstrings consistently
- Document public functions, classes, and modules
- Include parameter types, return types, and raised exceptions
